  <header class=3D"entry-header">
    <h1>Capital Gains Tax</h1>  </header>

  <div class=3D"entry-content">
    <p><span class=3D"TextRun SCXW122153417 BCX8" lang=3D"EN-US" xml:lang=
=3D"EN-US" data-contrast=3D"none"><span class=3D"NormalTextRun SCXW12215341=
7 BCX8">A capital gains tax is levied on the profit made from selling an as=
set and is often in addition to </span></span><a class=3D"Hyperlink SCXW122=
153417 BCX8" href=3D"https://taxfoundation.org/taxedu/glossary/corporate-in=
come-tax-cit/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener"><span class=3D=
"SCXW122153417 BCX8"><span class=3D"TextRun Underlined SCXW122153417 BCX8" =
lang=3D"EN-US" xml:lang=3D"EN-US" data-contrast=3D"none"><span class=3D"Nor=
malTextRun SCXW122153417 BCX8" data-ccp-charstyle=3D"Hyperlink">corporate i=
ncome taxes</span></span></span></a><span class=3D"TextRun SCXW122153417 BC=
X8" lang=3D"EN-US" xml:lang=3D"EN-US" data-contrast=3D"none"><span class=3D=
"NormalTextRun SCXW122153417 BCX8">, </span><span class=3D"NormalTextRun SC=
XW122153417 BCX8">frequently</span><span class=3D"NormalTextRun SCXW1221534=
17 BCX8"> resulting in </span></span><a class=3D"Hyperlink SCXW122153417 BC=
X8" href=3D"https://taxfoundation.org/taxedu/glossary/double-taxation/" tar=
get=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener"><span class=3D"SCXW122153417 BCX=
8"><span class=3D"TextRun Underlined SCXW122153417 BCX8" lang=3D"EN-US" xml=
:lang=3D"EN-US" data-contrast=3D"none"><span class=3D"NormalTextRun SCXW122=
153417 BCX8" data-ccp-charstyle=3D"Hyperlink">double taxation</span></span>=
</span></a><span class=3D"TextRun SCXW122153417 BCX8" lang=3D"EN-US" xml:la=
ng=3D"EN-US" data-contrast=3D"none"><span class=3D"NormalTextRun SCXW122153=
417 BCX8">. These taxes </span></span><a class=3D"Hyperlink SCXW122153417 B=
CX8" href=3D"https://taxfoundation.org/capital-gains-taxes/" target=3D"_bla=
nk" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener"><span class=3D"TextRun Underlined SCXW12215=
3417 BCX8" lang=3D"EN-US" xml:lang=3D"EN-US" data-contrast=3D"none"><span c=
lass=3D"NormalTextRun SCXW122153417 BCX8" data-ccp-charstyle=3D"Hyperlink">=
create </span></span></a><span class=3D"TextRun SCXW122153417 BCX8" lang=3D=
"EN-US" xml:lang=3D"EN-US" data-contrast=3D"none"><span class=3D"NormalText=
Run SCXW122153417 BCX8">a bias against saving, leading to a lower level of =
national income by encouraging present consumption over investment.</span><=
/span><span class=3D"EOP SCXW122153417 BCX8" data-ccp-props=3D"{&quot;13423=
3117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;=
335557856&quot;:16777215,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:360,=
&quot;335559740&quot;:240}">&nbsp;</span></p>
<hr>
    <h2>Definitions and Rates</h2>
<p><span data-contrast=3D"none">Capital assets generally </span><a href=3D"=
https://www.irs.gov/publications/p550#en_US_2024_publink100010479"><span da=
ta-contrast=3D"none">include</span></a><span data-contrast=3D"none"> everyt=
hing owned and used for personal purposes, pleasure, or investment, includi=
ng stocks, bonds, homes, cars, jewelry, and art. The purchase price of a ca=
pital asset is typically referred to as the asset=E2=80=99s basis. When the=
 asset is sold at a price higher than its basis, it results in a capital ga=
in; when the asset is sold for less than its basis, it results in a capital=
 loss. Although </span><a href=3D"https://taxfoundation.org/research/all/fe=
deral/capital-gains-taxes/"><span data-contrast=3D"none">capital gains taxe=
s</span></a><span data-contrast=3D"none"> typically apply to the returns fr=
om any capital asset, including housing, U.S. homeowners benefit from a gen=
erous </span><a href=3D"https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc701"><span data-con=
trast=3D"none">exemption</span></a><span data-contrast=3D"none"> for gains =
resulting from the sale of their primary residence, set at $250,000 for sin=
gle filers ($500,000 for joint filers).</span><span data-ccp-props=3D"{&quo=
t;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0=
,&quot;335557856&quot;:16777215,&quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quo=
t;:360,&quot;335559740&quot;:240}">&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span data-contrast=3D"none">In the United States, when a person realize=
s a capital gain, they face a tax on that gain. The tax rates vary dependin=
g on </span><a href=3D"https://www.irs.gov/taxtopics/tc409"><span data-cont=
rast=3D"none">two factors</span></a><span data-contrast=3D"none">: how long=
 the asset was held and the amount of income the taxpayer earns. If an asse=
t was held for less than one year and then sold for a profit, it is classif=
ied as a short-term capital gain and taxed as ordinary income. If an asset =
was held for more than one year and then sold for a profit, it is classifie=
d as a long-term capital gain. Table 1 indicates the tax rates for tax year=
 2025.</span><span data-ccp-props=3D"{&quot;134233117&quot;:false,&quot;134=
233118&quot;:false,&quot;201341983&quot;:0,&quot;335557856&quot;:16777215,&=
quot;335559738&quot;:0,&quot;335559739&quot;:360,&quot;335559740&quot;:240}=
">&nbsp;</span></p>
<h4>2025 Long-Term Capital Gains Tax Brackets</h4>
<div id=3D"tablepress-242_wrapper" class=3D"dataTables_wrapper no-footer">
<table id=3D"tablepress-242" class=3D"tablepress tablepress-id-242 tablepre=
